Capacity formula

To make things simpler, lets consider only the ingredients of capacity that we have studied here as a function of age \(a\):

\[ C(a) \propto \frac{p(a) \times i(a)}{g(a)} e^{-\frac{g(a)}{m(a)}} \] Everything else will be a multiplicative constant. We dont care too much about the exact values of such a constant because we will express everything relative to the 4-day-old group. Futhermore, in the results, we will learn from experiment 3 that \(m(a)\) does not change with age. So, for figure 5 we will be able to simply consider the following formula:

\[ C(a) \propto \frac{p(a) \times i(a)}{g(a)} e^{-\frac{g(a)}{m}} \] Sporozoite prevalences \(p(a)\) and sporozoite intensities (given infection) \(i(a)\) are informed by experiment 1 and mosquitoes survival rates \(g(a)\) are informed by experiment 2. We will assume that the vector competence and survival are independent from each other. Well assume that \(p(a)\) follows a beta distribution, the parameters of which will be estimated from the binomial estimate and its confidence interval from the presence/absence raw data. Values for \(p(a)\) will then be randomly drawed from this beta distribution. Given that results from experiment 1 show that the distributions of sporozoites intensities do not look like any clear distribution, it will probably be better to perform non-parametric bootstrapping of the data in order to generate values of sporozoites intensities. As for the mosquito survival rates, we will take the estimates from the mixed-effect model of experiment 2.

Sporozoite prevalences

A function that converts confidence intervals boundary values of a proportion into shape parameters of a beta distribution:

ci2pars <- function(ci, f, pars, p = .95) {
  p <- (1 - p) / 2
  
  f_par <- function(par1, par2) {
    c(f(p, par1, par2), f(1 - p, par1, par2))
  }

  f_fit <- function(pars) {
    sum((f_par(pars[1], pars[2]) - ci)^2)
  }
  
  optim(pars, f_fit)$par
}

The shape parameters of the beta distribution of the mean sporozoites prevalences (\(p(a)\)):

p_par <- fig2 |> 
  group_by(age_class) |> 
  summarize(x   = sum(positive), n = length(positive)) |> 
  mutate(prop   = map2(x, n, prop.test),
         ci     = map(prop, magrittr::extract2, "conf.int"),
         shapes = map(ci, ci2pars, qbeta, 1:2)) |> 
  pull(shapes) |> 
  setNames(age_names)

Experiment 3

fig4 <- "data/fig4_EIP_data.txt" |>
  read_delim() |> 
  select(dpi, spz) |> 
  na.exclude() |> 
  mutate_at("spz", as.logical)
mod <- glm(spz ~ dpi, binomial, fig4)
xs <- seq(min(fig4$dpi), max(fig4$dpi), le = 1000)
ys <- predict(mod, data.frame(dpi = xs), se.fit = TRUE)
fit <- ys$fit
invtransf <- family(mod)$linkinv
low <- invtransf(ys$fit - 1.96 * ys$se.fit)
upp <- invtransf(ys$fit + 1.96 * ys$se.fit)
fit <- invtransf(fit)

plot(xs, fit, type = "l")
lines(xs, low, lty = 2)
lines(xs, upp, lty = 2)
abline(h = .5)

ci <- tibble(xs, low, upp)

m <- ci2pars(c(filter(ci, .5 < upp)$xs[1], filter(ci, .5 < low)$xs[1]), qgamma, 1:2)

Simulating data

simulate <- function(p, i, g, N = 10000) {
  p_val <- do.call(rbeta, c(list(N), unname(p)))
  i_val <- sample(i, N, replace = TRUE)
  g_val <- 1 / sample(g, N, replace = TRUE)
  m_val <- do.call(rgamma, c(list(N), m))
  p_val * i_val * exp(-g_val) / g_val
}
sim_age4           <- simulate(p_par$`4-day-old`,   i$`4-day-old`, age4)
sim_age12_ExpInf   <- simulate(p_par$`12-day-old`, i$`12-day-old`, age12$`Exposed-infected`)
sim_age12_ExpNoinf <- simulate(p_par$`12-day-old`, i$`12-day-old`, age12$`Exposed-uninfected`)
sim_age12_Uninf    <- simulate(p_par$`12-day-old`, i$`12-day-old`, age12$`Uninfected control`)
hist(log(sim_age4))

hist(log(sim_age12_ExpInf))

hist(log(sim_age12_ExpNoinf))

hist(log(sim_age12_Uninf))
